Consider connecting the two vectors into a right triangle similar the
picture to the right\includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{../json_data/MATH152/April_2011/Dot_Product.png}. To get the
component of $\mathbf{x}$ onto $\mathbf{y}$, we follow like in the
picture and
take,\\\begin{align*}
\textrm{proj}_\mathbf{y}\mathbf{x}=|\mathbf{x}|\cos(\theta)\hat{\mathbf{y}}
\end{align*}\\where
$\theta$ is the angle between the vectors $\mathbf{x}$ and $\mathbf{y}$
and $\hat{\mathbf{y}}$ is a unit vector in the direction of
$\mathbf{y}$. We can rewrite $\cos(\theta)$ in terms of the
{dot (scalar) product}
as,\\\begin{align*}
\cos(\theta)=\frac{\mathbf{x}\cdot\mathbf{y}}{|\mathbf{x}||\mathbf{y}|}.
\end{align*}\\Therefore,
the projection of $\mathbf{x}$ onto $\mathbf{y}$
is\\\begin{align*}
\textrm{proj}_\mathbf{y}\mathbf{x}=\frac{\mathbf{x}\cdot\mathbf{y}}{|\mathbf{y}|}\hat{\mathbf{y}}=\frac{\mathbf{x}\cdot\mathbf{y}}{|\mathbf{y}|^2}\mathbf{y}
\end{align*}\\where
we have recognized
that\\\begin{align*}
\hat{\mathbf{y}}=\frac{\mathbf{y}}{|\mathbf{y}|}.
\end{align*}\\Computing
the dot product we get,\\\begin{align*}
\mathbf{x}\cdot\mathbf{y}=0-3+2=-1
\end{align*}\\and for
the magnitude of
$\mathbf{y}$,\\\begin{align*}
|\mathbf{y}|=\sqrt{1^2+1^2+1^2}=\sqrt{3}.
\end{align*}\\Therefore
we get that the projection of $\mathbf{x}$ onto $\mathbf{y}$
is,\\\begin{align*}
\textrm{proj}_\mathbf{y}\mathbf{x}=\frac{\mathbf{x}\cdot\mathbf{y}}{|\mathbf{y}|^2}\mathbf{y}=-\frac{1}{3}\mathbf{y}=\left[-\frac{1}{3},-\frac{1}{3},-\frac{1}{3}\right].
\end{align*}\\
